snippet.textDisplay:
@31:23 - Sean, on Christmas Eve last year you may have heard a random person say "Ding ding ding" while you and Evelien walked along. That was me freaking out because I had seen you out and about, me having finished work early but missed my bus but noticed the two of you through some freak coincidence. I'd been meaning to draw you something in case I ever accidentally saw you (I work in Brighton) but I never did and so when I DID see you I didn't have anything to give you. I didn't want to just approach you and freak out, especially if you were having a bad or a stressful day (it was Christmas Eve after all). So sorry for nerding out in my own way but you absolutely made my day (I told everyone who would listen I saw you and only 2 or 3 of those people even knew who you were XD).

Just seeing this point in the video I wanted to say that my excitement was purely for you and for Evelien and for this wonderful world you have created on YouTube for all of us. I didn't need to take a photo with you, or ask for an autograph, just seeing you like you would see thousands of other people in the day, just that was enough. You're a fantastic and beautiful human being, with so much love to give, you help make me a better person. Thank you.

snippet.textDisplay:
ETA: in response to Jack's mentioning his prior insecurities regarding his intelligence

Just wanted to give my two cents on the idea of intelligence. There are so many types of intelligence but when people talk about being smart it's almost always in relation with academics. And academic intelligence has a lot of the aspects that are tested and reflected in a person's IQ.

But like I said there are so many types. I'm lucky to have pretty good academic intelligence plus some street smarts. But I've always admired Jack for his emotional intelligence. He's able to communicate his emotions, thoughts, and ideas so easily. I figure he could maintain an intellectual conversation on certain social topics quite well, whereas I struggle to explain and articulate my thoughts (but writing them is easier than a fast-paced situation like talking).

ALSO to those students out there who feel stupid, or people like my friends who are like "naw I'm too dumb for university/college". Education is not only for the highly intelligent. Postsecondary success depends more on your time management, ability to cope, study strategies, and motivation than any sort of academic intelligence. From my experience, academic intelligence allows people to learn concepts faster, but that doesn't mean most people can't learn those concepts too. The majority who go on to a successful career are individuals who put in the effort and time required to get there. Not the people with the highest IQs.

Thanks for coming to my Ted Talk.
